    <title>Combined summary - Taproot: Privacy preserving switchable scripting</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T00:09:53.586132+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-February/015703.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developer Gregory Maxwell proposed Taproot, a new approach to Merkelized Abstract Syntax Trees (MAST) that would make smart contracts indistinguishable from regular payments. Taproot supports any number of participants and can be made indistinguishable from 1-of-1 using MuSig. There are concerns about paying directly to a public key instead of a public key hash, but the proposal is generally well-received. The email thread discusses the use of merkelized scripts on bitcoin-dev. The main benefits of MAST are efficiency and privacy. The author argues that any contract with a fixed, finite participant set can be represented as an OR between an N-of-N and a more complex contract. There are concerns about quantum attacks against ECC, but hashing provided for quantum resistance may not be as effective as previously thought. Direct SPK use can enable efficient ZKP over the UTXO set for private solvency proofs, although it isn't mandatory.Regarding the security of Bitcoin addresses in light of quantum computing advances, there are debates on whether to use public keys or pubkey hashes in the Taproot proposal. While hashing provides some level of quantum resistance, it may not be meaningful enough. Discussions on the Bitcoin-dev mailing list have proposed various solutions to combat the potential threat of quantum computing attacks on Bitcoin. One approach is to use quantum-safe zero-knowledge proofs (ZKP), although this would likely require a hardfork to apply to old transactions. Alternatively, the Fawkes signature scheme and the Taproot delegating CHECKSIG proposal by Gregory Maxwell have been suggested as sufficient for the foreseeable future. The bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing various proposals and concerns related to the interception and insertion of commitments in transactions in the blockchain. One proposal involves committing H(classic_pk, tx) and tx to the blockchain and waiting for confirmation before revealing classic_pk in the blockchain. Another proposed solution is Taproot, a delegating CHECKSIG that can make the special case of a top-level "threshold-signature OR arbitrary-conditions" indistinguishable from a normal one-party signature without any overhead at all. In addition, there are debates about whether paying directly to a public key instead of a public key hash in Bitcoin is a step backwards in terms of resistance to quantum attacks against ECC. The bitcoin community is currently discussing the adoption of Taproot, which has been proposed by Gregory Maxwell as a superior approach to a native-MAST template. However, some members of the bitcoin community argue that while Taproot may offer benefits, it is not optimal and that permissionless innovation should come before application specialization.Overall, the discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list revolves around finding solutions to minimize the risks of interception and insertion of commitments in transactions while ensuring the integrity of the blockchain.Bitcoin developer Matt Corallo expressed concerns regarding the adoption of a new approach without support for a privacy-encouraging wrapper proposed by Greg. While some believe that Taproot may offer benefits, others argue that enabling features in a generic way first and then creating specialized templates is the correct approach. BIPs 116 and 117 provide a reusable component that enables a generic form of MAST while also allowing other applications like honeypots, key trees, and script delegation, making the MAST feature available for use in production by the wider community.The email conversation between Tim Ruffing and the Bitcoin-dev community discusses a proposal for preventing theft in a blockchain transaction. The revised approach involves publishing encrypted transactions as the commitment, then publishing the key to propagate it quickly to reduce the risk of an attacker creating their own commitment hash for a theft transaction.The Bitcoin community is actively exploring new approaches to enhance security and privacy while enabling efficient transactions. There were various proposals put forward, including the use of Taproot, Merkelized ScriptPubKeys, and zero-knowledge proofs, but there were also concerns about potential weaknesses and risks associated with these proposals.</summary>
